met by a dolphin,“ who sometimes swam before him, and sometimes behind him, then played round him, and at last took him upon his back, then let him down, and afterwards took him up again: and thus carried the poor srightened buy out into the deepest part; when immediately he tums back again to the shore, and lands him among his companions. The farne of this remarkable accident spread through the town, and crowds of people flocked round the boy (whom they viewed as a kind of prodigy) to ask him questione, hear his story and repeat it.

The next day the shore was lined with multitudes of spectators all attentively observing the ocean, and (what indeed is almost itself an ocean) the lake, ln the meanwhile the boys swam as usual, and among the rest, the youth l arn speaking of went into the lake, but with more caution than before. The dolphin punctually appeared again and came to the boy, who together with his companions swam away with the ut- most precipitation. The dolphin, as it were, to invite and recall them, bounded and dived up aud down, winding about in a thousand different circles. This he praetised for several days together, till the people (accustomed from their infuncy to the sea) began to be ashamed of their timidity. They ventured there- fore to advance nearer, playing with him and calling him to them, while he, in return, suffered himself to be touched and stroked. Use rendered them more courageous: the boy, in particular, who first made the experimeut, swam by the side of him, and leap- iug upon his back, was carried to and fro in that manner: he fancies the dolphin knows and is fond of him, and he returns its fondness.
